ofessional snooker player, 1980 world champion, 3-time Masters champion}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2010}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n|name             = Cliff Thorburn\n|honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|size=100|country=CAN|CM}}\n|image            = Cliff-Thorburn-2010.jpg\n|image_size       = 250px\n|caption          =\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1948|1|16}}\n|birth_place      = [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], [[British Columbia]]\n| Sport country   = {{CAN}}\n| Nickname        = {{unbulleted list|The Grinder|Champagne Cliff}}\n| Professional    = 1972&ndash;1996\n| High ranking    = '''[[List of world number one snooker players|1]]''' ([[Snooker world rankings 1981/1982|1981/82]])\n| Prize money     = \u00a3988,098 \n| High break      = '''[[maximum break|147]]''': <small>(2 times) </small>\n| Century break   = 92\n| Ranking wins    = 2\n| Other wins      = 18\n| World champ     = [[World Snooker Championship 1980|1980]]\n}}\n\n'''Clifford Charles Devlin''' '''Thorburn''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}} (born January 16, 1948) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] retired professional [[snooker]] player. Nicknamed \"The Grinder\" because of his slow, determined style of play, he won the [[World Snooker Championship]] in [[1980 World Snooker Championship|1980]], defeating [[Alex Higgins]] 18\u201316 in the final to become the first world champion in the sport's modern era from outside the [[United Kingdom]]. He remains the only world champion from the [[Americas]]. \n\nThorburn was runner-up in two other World Championships, losing 21\u201325 to [[John Spencer (snooker player)|John Spencer]] in the [[1977 World Snooker Championship|1977]] final (the first ever played at Sheffield's [[Crucible Theatre]]) and 6\u201318 to [[Steve Davis]] in the [[1983 World Snooker Championship|1983]] final. One of his most celebrated moments came during his second-round encounter with [[Terry Griffiths]] in 1983, when he became the first player to compile a [[maximum break]] in a World Championship match. He was the second player (after Davis) to make a 147 break in professional competition.\n\nThorburn's other notable achievements include holding the [[List of world number one snooker players|number one ranking]] during the [[Snooker season 1981/1982|1981/82 season]] and winning the prestigious invitational [[Masters (snooker)|Masters]] three times, in [[1983 Masters (snooker)|1983]], [[1985 Masters (snooker)|1985]], and [[1986 Masters (snooker)|1986]]. This made him the first player to win the Masters more than once and the first to retain the title. \n\nHe retired from the professional tour in 1996 and was inducted into [[Canada's Sports Hall of Fame]] in 2001.<ref name=\"ca\">{{cite web | url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/five-enter-canada-s-sports-hall-1.258115|title=Five enter Canada's Sports Hall|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> At the age of 70, he won the [[2018 Seniors Masters]] at the Crucible Theatre, becoming the oldest player to win a world seniors title.\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nThorburn first went to [[England]] to play snooker professionally in the early 70s. He had met [[John Spencer (snooker player)|John Spencer]] in [[Canada]], who had advised him to go to the UK to improve his game. He was soon considered a contender for tournaments, and finished runner-up in the world championship in 1977.\n\n===1980s===\nCliff Thorburn met [[Alex Higgins]] in the final of the [[1980 World Snooker Championship|1980 World Championship]]. He won the match 18\u201316 to take the championship,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/23112009/58/cliff-thorburn.html |title=Then and Now: Cliff Thorburn |date=17 November 2009 |publisher=[[Eurosport]] |website=Yahoo! Sport |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425011253/https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/23112009/58/cliff-thorburn.html |archive-date=25 April 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and rose to number two in the [[Snooker world rankings 1980/1981|world rankings]]. The [[BBC]]'s coverage of the final had been interrupted by the broadcast of live footage of the [[Iranian Embassy Siege|SAS storming the Iranian Embassy]]. The following season, Thorburn reached number one in the [[Snooker world rankings 1981/1982|world rankings]].\n\nIn 1983, Thorburn was made a Member of the [[Order of Canada]]. That same year, he became the first player to make a [[maximum break]] at the [[World Snooker Championship|World Championship]]. He compiled the break in the fourth frame of his second round match against [[Terry Griffiths]] (a match he went on to win 13\u201312). While he was completing the break, play stopped on the tournament's second table because his friend and fellow Canadian [[Bill Werbeniuk]] wanted to watch. He subsequently went on to reach the final, but lost to then world number 1 [[Steve Davis]]. His wife had a miscarriage during his semi-final, but Thorburn refused to blame this for his loss, instead saying that he was fatigued after his three back-to-back final-frame victories: a 13\u201312 win over Terry Griffiths in the second round; another 13\u201312 win over [[Kirk Stevens]] in the quarter finals; and a gruelling 16\u201315 victory (from 13\u201315 behind) in his semi-final against [[Tony Knowles (snooker player)|Tony Knowles]], which finished at 2:30am and left him physically exhausted before the final which commenced later that same day. He stated that, after finishing the semi-final in the early hours of the morning, he simply had nothing left for the final less than thirteen hours later against the in-form Steve Davis, who eventually defeated him 18\u20136, with a session to spare.\n\nThorburn was a three-time champion of [[Masters (snooker)|The Masters]], the most prestigious non-ranking event on the snooker calendar for many years, during its tenure at the Wembley Conference Centre near London, England. He defeated [[Ray Reardon]] 9\u20137 in the [[1983 Masters (snooker)|1983]] final, [[Doug Mountjoy]] 9\u20136 in [[1985 Masters (snooker)|1985]], and [[Jimmy White]] 9\u20135 in [[1986 Masters (snooker)|1986]]. He became the first player ever to retain the Masters title.\n\nHe enjoyed a resurgence in form during the [[Snooker season 1984/1985|1984/1985 season]]. He made the final of the [[1984 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]], where he lost to [[Dennis Taylor]] 2\u201310. In the semi-final, Thorburn had unexpectedly beaten tournament favourite Steve Davis 9\u20137. He also made the final of the [[1985 Classic (snooker)|Classic]] in January 1985, where he met [[Willie Thorne]] in the final, with Thorne winning 13\u20138. Thorburn was again runner-up in the [[1986 Classic (snooker)|1986 Classic]], this time losing to Jimmy White in the final 12\u201313. Thorburn looked certain to win the title but White got a snooker in the deciding frame on the final pink and potted pink and black to win the title.{{fact|date=March 2019}}\n\nThorburn enjoyed success in the [[1985 Scottish Masters|1985]] and [[1986 Scottish Masters|1986]] Scottish Masters, an invitational event which opened the snooker season. He defeated Willie Thorne 9\u20137 in the 1985 final, and Alex Higgins 9\u20138 the following year. He won the opening ranking event in the [[Snooker season 1985/1986|1985/1986 snooker calendar]], the [[1985 Matchroom Trophy|Matchroom Trophy]], where he beat Jimmy White in the final 12\u201310, having trailed 0\u20137 and 4\u20138. He was then runner-up in the same event the following two seasons.\n\n===Later years===\n\nThorburn last qualified for the World Championship in [[1994 World Snooker Championship|1994]], where he faced [[Nigel Bond]] in the first round. Thorburn led by 9\u20132 but eventually lost 9\u201310. In 2001, he was inducted into [[Canada's Sports Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"ca\" /> The same year he won the pro-am [[Canadian Amateur Championship (snooker)]]; he had previously won the tournament in 1974, 1975, 1976, and 1977.<ref name=\"cbsa.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsa.ca/cbsa-champions-list.php |title=CBSA Champions & Runner-Ups |date=2009 |publisher=Canadian Billiards & Snooker Association |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715130006/https://www.cbsa.ca/cbsa-champions-list.php |archive-date=15 July 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2006 World Snooker Championship|2006 World Championship]], Thorburn flew to Sheffield to unveil a life-size painting of the first televised maximum break that he made at the tournament in 1983. Painted by the artist Michael Myers, the work is on display at the Macdonald St. Paul's Hotel in Sheffield.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/whats-on/artist-puts-a-perfect-frame-on-the-map-1-267992|title=Artist puts a perfect frame on the map...|date=15 April 2006|work=[[Sheffield Star]]|access-date=27 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427164844/https://www.thestar.co.uk/whats-on/artist-puts-a-perfect-frame-on-the-map-1-267992|archive-date=27 April 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2010, Thorburn returned to the UK to compete on the Snooker Legends Tour where he faced Alex Higgins, Jimmy White and [[John Parrott]].\n\nHis manager Darryl McKerrow was killed in a hunting accident during the mid-1980s.{{fact|date=March 2019}} \n\nThorburn was fined \u00a310,000 and banned for two ranking tournaments in 1988 after failing a drug test for cocaine.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=10 April 1998 |title=Snooker: Three players fail drug tests but remain anonymous |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-three-players-fail-drug-tests-but-remain-anonymous-1155528.html |work=The Independent |access-date=29 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416152110/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/snooker-three-players-fail-drug-tests-but-remain-anonymous-1155528.html |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe is the father of two children, Jamie and Andrew. Thorburn won around C$2.5 million in prize money during his 25-year career but also received a considerable income from sources including billiards equipment endorsements, exhibition games, a snooker instruction book and an autobiography, ''Playing for Keeps'', published in 1987.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://isbnsearch.org/isbn/9781852250119 |title=Playing for Keeps |author1=Cliff Thorburn |author2=Clive Everton |date=December 1987 |publisher=Partridge Press |isbn=978-1852250119 |access-date=2019-05-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504090716/https://isbnsearch.org/isbn/9781852250119 |archive-date=2019-05-04 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n<div style=\"width:auto; overflow:scroll\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0 1em 0 0; border:1px #aaa solid; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:85%\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament''' \n! [[Snooker season 1972/1973|1972/<br/>73]]\n! [[Snooker season 1973/1974|1973/<br/>74]]\n! [[Snooker season 1974/1975|1974/<br/>75]]\n! [[Snooker season 1975/1976|1975/<br/>76]]\n! [[Snooker season 1976/1977|1976/<br/>77]]\n! [[Snooker season 1977/1978|1977/<br/>78]]\n! [[Snooker season 1978/1979|1978/<br/>79]]\n! [[Snooker season 1979/1980|1979/<br/>80]]\n! [[Snooker season 1980/1981|1980/<br/>81]]\n! [[Snooker season 1981/1982|1981/<br/>82]]\n! [[Snooker season 1982/1983|1982/<br/>83]]\n! [[Snooker season 1983/1984|1983/<br/>84]]\n! [[Snooker season 1984/1985|1984/<br/>85]]\n! [[Snooker season 1985/1986|1985/<br/>86]]\n! [[Snooker season 1986/1987|1986/<br/>87]] \n! [[Snooker season 1987/1988|1987/<br/>88]] \n! [[Snooker season 1988/1989|1988/<br/>89]] \n! [[Snooker season 1989/1990|1989/<br/>90]] \n! [[Snooker season 1990/1991|1990/<br/>91]]\n! [[Snooker season 1991/1992|1991/<br/>92]]\n! [[Snooker season 1992/1993|1992/<br/>93]]\n! [[Snooker season 1993/1994|1993/<br/>94]]\n! [[Snooker season 1994/1995|1994/<br/>95]]\n! [[Snooker season 1995/1996|1995/<br/>96]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web|title=Ranking History|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=7 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219070820/http://www.snooker.org/Rnk/history.asp|archive-date=19 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" colspan=\"4\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|No ranking system\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1976/1977|13]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1977/1978|6]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1978/1979|5]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1979/1980|5]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1980/1981|2]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1981/1982|1]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1982/1983|3]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1983/1984|3]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1984/1985|3]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1985/1986|2]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1986/1987|2]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1987/1988|4]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1988/1989|6]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1989/1990|7]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1990/1991|18]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1991/1992|36]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1992/1993|36]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1993/1994|41]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1994/1995|54]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 1995/1996|41]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"50\" | '''Ranking tournaments'''\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Dubai Classic|Thailand Classic]]<ref group=\"nb\">The event was also called the Dubai Masters (1988/1989) and Dubai Classic (1989/1990\u20131994/1995)</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"16\"|Tournament 